snippet.textDisplay: So simmering the mixture longer at the beginning would have made it thicker too.  The simmer/boil is what allows the arrowroot flour to thicken the mixture.  Looks delicious!  Another recipe I read said to use the inside of a vanilla bean rather than extract.  You can also make vanilla sugar for the top by mixing 2 cups of sugar with the insides of a vanilla bean and burying the outside of the bean in the sugar and letting it sit for 2 weeks.  That would be extra tasty for the topping.

snippet.textDisplay: This is amazing. But the real question is: does this creme brûlée taste like coconut? Because as someone with a dairy allergy, every dessert with coconut milk as a base always seems to have a coconut aftertaste that I don’t like. I’ve been wondering about a vegan alternative to sweetened condensed milk I could use in a family cookie recipe I have, but a coconut taste would ruin that cookie. I want it to taste as close to the dairy version as possible without giving me symptoms. Off to Google nondairy equivalents to sweetened condensed milk I guess 🤷‍♀️ thanks for giving me a place to start though!
snippet.textOriginal: This is amazing. But the real question is: does this creme brûlée taste like coconut? Because as someone with a dairy allergy, every dessert with coconut milk as a base always seems to have a coconut aftertaste that I don’t like. snippet.textDisplay: Hi! Spaniard here. We call it "crema catalana" and I make it every week at the restaurant I work at. The way Julian did it wasn't actually correct but eih... as long as it tastes good, who cares? You have to put milk in a pot, (or in this case your vegan substitute) add cinnamon sticks and lemon/orange peels (just the skin, not the white part because that's bitter) let it boil but just for a minute. Cover the pot and leave it like that for 12 hours or just 15 min if you can't wait XD. But if you let it overnight it will taste better. Then remove the cinnamon and the peels, low heat and add corn starch to thicken it, maybe some blended cashews, nutritional yeast, and sugar (maybe some turmeric for the color) and mix it well.  Pour the crème into your ramekins, put them in the fridge and BAM! Also, for those of you who don't have a torch, use a spoon. Warm it up with a lighter or with your stove.
